The memo argues for the president's authority to conduct military operations against terrorists and their supporters to protect the US.
It grants Bush the power to wage preemptive war, even against groups not linked to 9/11.
Gonzales, responsible for legal frameworks, defended Bush's actions in line with US values.
The administration downplayed the memos' significance, but critics argue otherwise.
The debate over torture definitions continues, with concerns about abuse and secrecy.
The president's perceived imperial right to bypass laws remains contentious, sparking calls for accountability and transparency in government actions.
